At Kmart, this helps us streamline our inventory processes so that we can focus on what’s most important, delivering outstanding customer service and enhancing the overall shopping experience. </p><p><strong>So what technology do we use to automate our inventory tracking?</strong></p><p><strong>......introducing TORY!</strong></p><p>TORY is a self-driving autonomous robot that has one job, to roam the entire store capturing data. This data allows us to digitise previously manual tasks, so team members can get them done quicker, so they can focus on what really matters, the customer! </p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><p><strong>So what does TORY do?</strong></p><p>Using RFID (Radio Frequency Identification) technology, TORY captures data from an RFID tag. RFID tags are placed or embedded in price tags and when TORY is nearby, it emits a signal, activating the tag. Once activated, TORY captures the data on the tag. This rich inventory data tells us exactly what stock we have and where it is in our store. </p><p>Select the markers to learn more about TORY.</p><p><strong>Sensors</strong></p><p>TORY has three sensors attached that helps to safely navigate around people and objects. Click each benefit to learn more.</p><p><strong>TORY RFID Benefits &amp; Guidelines</strong></p><p><strong>Inventory Accuracy</strong></p><p>TORY can complete a full store run to capture all tags, free from obstruction.<br /><strong>This helps</strong> eliminate wasted time searching for stock that doesn’t exist, reduce online exceptions, and create happier customers and team members.</p><p><strong>Accurate Location</strong></p><p>Technology is reliable and processes are in place.<br />Physical and virtual store setups match — ensuring <strong>Right Stock, Right Container</strong>.<br /><strong>This helps</strong> team members easily find and sell every single item in the store (both online and offline), maximising sales and team efficiency.</p><p><strong>Accurate Count</strong></p><p>BOH (Back of House) areas are organised into containers to ensure only relevant items are counted.<br />Shop floors and BOH have been prepared to a minimum standard.<br /><strong>This helps</strong> ensure that all items being counted have RFID tags, and that TORY can move around the store each night and get within a metre of each tag.</p><p><strong>Everyone is Safe</strong></p><p>TORY can safely navigate both the shop floor and back of house.<br />Team members are trained to perform all manual and digital tasks safely.<br /><strong>This helps</strong> team members follow correct procedures when moving TORY manually — always referring to learning materials and avoiding direct contact where possible.</p><p><em>Lesson 4 of 6</em></p><p><strong>What digital tasks are performed in your digital store?</strong></p><p><strong>RFID and Tory – How does it work?</strong></p><p>You previously learnt that rich inventory data is captured by TORY from a microchip on an RFID tag. TORY only has one job, to capture the data from that microchip. You can also use a hand wand to capture the same RFID data.</p><p>Click each label below to learn more about how it works.</p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p><p><strong>RFID Tracking System Overview</strong></p><p><strong>RFID enabled price tags</strong><br />RFID tags are placed on items. RFID readers send a pulse to RFID tags, which activate (vibrate) and send data back to the reader. Tags that have the “EPC” icon already contain an RFID tag.</p><p><strong>TORY – Robotic RFID reader</strong><br />Tory self-drives and counts 1,000 tags per second, meaning we can do this daily in stores.</p><p><strong>Hand Wand – Manual RFID reader</strong><br />A hand wand can also be used to read the data on the tag.</p><p><strong>Accurate RFID tag locations</strong><br />Tory pinpoints the location of each tag, so we know where it is in the store.</p><p><strong>TORY’s run</strong></p><p>Each night, TORY will perform a run around the store, capturing all the RFID data.  This run is the first task in the process.  To see what happens next, click the icons in the wheel below for more information.</p><ol><li>TORY Awakens<ol><li>The run commences</li></ol></li><li>DATA COLLECTED<ol><li>As TORY roams the store, apparel data is collected. Size style colour and overall variant</li></ol></li><li>TORY Docks at charger<ol><li>Once complete TORY will dock. Data waits until all counts are completed</li></ol></li><li>TORY is moved<ol><li>If required, TORY relocates to a second Charger, ready to collect data from another area of the store i.e a 2<sup>nd</sup> floor accessible by lift</li></ol></li><li>All TORY runs completed<ol><li>Once all TORY runs have been completed it is ready to be uploaded</li></ol></li><li>Manual Hand Scan<ol><li>If required a manual scan is done with a hand wand, to complete the full count in areas the TORY can’t reach i.e Mezzanine</li></ol></li><li>FULL DATA CONSOLIDATION<ol><li>All data is consolidated, ready to merge with stock on hand data</li></ol></li><li>Accurate Stock on hand data<ol><li>Stock on hand is updated and now we have an accurate view of stock levels by style and size, color etc. We even know where it is located</li></ol></li><li>Backfill task created<ol><li>Now we know where items are needed on the shop floor so digital backfill task is generated to fullfiill minimum display unit MDU requirements</li></ol></li><li>Shop floor backfilled<ol><li>Team members fill the shop floor with stock was sold ensuring greater visibility</li></ol></li><li>Online Picking / Customer Service<ol><li>With accurate stock and the location of items online picking and customer service become quicker and more efficient!</li></ol></li></ol><p><strong>What is Radio Frequency Identification (RFID) ?</strong></p><p>Radio Frequency Identification or RFID is a sticker that holds a lot of information about the item it's on. It can contain product information such as:</p><ul><li>Keycodes</li><li>Style</li><li>Colour</li><li>Size</li><li>Price</li><li>Status</li></ul><p><strong>Microchip</strong></p><p><strong>This dot is the microchip.
